Alevin-Fry Comparison of Resolution Modes

Ally Hawkins for CCDL

In this notebook we are comparing the use of the cr-like resolution in alevin-fry to the cr-like-em resolution. Previously in our benchmarking analysis we made the decision to use alevin-fry with the splici index and selective alignment (salign) for all samples, single-nucleus and single-cell. The one remaining question was about resolution. Alevin-fry using the splici index is recommended to be used in USA mode which is compatible with both cr-like and cr-like-em, so we have chosen to use one of these two methods. The difference between cr-like and cr-like-em is that the cr-like-em will use an expectation maximization algorithm to resolve multi-mapped reads, while cr-like will discard those reads.

Data in this notebook have been analyzed using alevin-fry 0.4.0 and salmon 1.5.1.

Here I am looking at comparisons of per cell QC metrics.

# merge coldata df with quant_info

  # rename tool to be either cellranger or alevin-fry

                   by = c("tool" = "tool",

  # rename the not_alevin to cellranger for plotting purposes
  dplyr::mutate(alevin_resolution = ifelse(alevin_resolution == "not_alevin", "cellranger", alevin_resolution))
# split into cell and nucleus coldata
cell_coldata_qc <- coldata_info_df %>%
  dplyr::filter(seq_unit == "cell")

nucleus_coldata_qc <- coldata_info_df %>%
  dplyr::filter(seq_unit == "nucleus") %>%
  dplyr::filter(index_type == "splici")

Per Cell QC Metrics

All Cells

Let’s briefly look at the UMI/cell and genes detected/cell when looking at all cells with these methods.

ggplot(nucleus_coldata_qc, aes(x = tool, y = sum, fill = alevin_resolution)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  facet_grid(~ sample) +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) + 
  ylab("UMI/cell") + 
  xlab("") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0,30000))

ggplot(nucleus_coldata_qc, aes(x = tool, y = detected, fill = alevin_resolution)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  facet_grid(~ sample) +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) + 
  ylab("Genes detected/cell") + 
  xlab("") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0,10000))

As seen previously, when looking at all cells across all tools, we see that alevin-fry appears to detect lower UMI/cell and genes detected/cell than cellranger regardless of resolution. This is most likely due to the fact that alevin-fry detects more cells than cellranger and is an artifact of the filtering methods. There is a population of cells passing filtering in alevin-fry with lower UMI/cell and genes detected/cell that should probably be filtered out.

Shared cells only

To be sure that is the case, let’s look at the shared cells only. Here we also want to compare the differences between the two resolution modes of alevin-fry.

# filter for cells that are found in all configurations of alevin + cellranger
cell_counts <- cell_coldata_qc %>%

The cr-like-em resolution actually looks more similar to cellranger than the cr-like when looking at UMI/cell, but when looking at genes/cell you do see a shift upwards in the cr-like-em. Cellranger appears to be somewhere in the middle with overall no major differences between these resolutions and cellranger so I would be inclined to use cr-like-em to resolve multi-mapped reads.

Gene overlap

Let’s look at if there is a difference in the actual genes that are detected overall between using cr-like and cr-like-em or if we are just picking up more genes/cell

# make a function to filter sces by subset of cells and re-calculate feature stats
filter_sce <- function(sce, cells){
  cells_to_keep <- colnames(sce) %in% cells
  sce[, cells_to_keep] %>%
    scater::addPerFeatureQC()
}
# split into cell and nucleus 
resolution <- c('cr-like', 'cr-like-em')
cell_sces <- list(cr_like_sce[1:2],
                  cr_like_em_sce[1:2])
nucleus_sces <- list(cr_like_sce[3:4],
                     cr_like_em_sce[3:4])

names(cell_sces) <- resolution
names(nucleus_sces) <- resolution

# filter list of sces based on common cells 
cell_sces_filtered <- cell_sces %>%
  purrr::map(
    ~ purrr::map(.x, filter_sce, cells = common_cells)
  )

nucleus_sces_filtered <- nucleus_sces %>%
  purrr::map(
    ~ purrr::map(.x, filter_sce, cells = common_nuclei)
  )

# grab rowdata and combine into dataframe to be used for plotting
cell_rowdata_filtered <- cell_sces %>% 
  purrr::map_df(
    ~ purrr::map_df(.x, scpcaTools::rowdata_to_df, .id = "quant_dir"),
    .id = "alevin_resolution"
  )

nucleus_rowdata_filtered <- nucleus_sces %>% 
  purrr::map_df(
    ~ purrr::map_df(.x, scpcaTools::rowdata_to_df, .id = "quant_dir"),
    .id = "alevin_resolution"
  )
# merge into one dataframe 
all_rowdata_filtered <- rbind(cell_rowdata_filtered, nucleus_rowdata_filtered)

# join with quant info to get sample names 
all_rowdata_filtered <- all_rowdata_filtered %>%
  dplyr::left_join(quant_info)
cr_like_genes <- all_rowdata_filtered %>%
  dplyr::filter(alevin_resolution == "cr-like") %>%
  dplyr::pull(gene_id) %>%
  unique()

cr_like_em_genes <- all_rowdata_filtered %>%
  dplyr::filter(alevin_resolution == "cr-like-em") %>%
  dplyr::pull(gene_id) %>%
  unique()
gene_overlap <- intersect(cr_like_genes, cr_like_em_genes)
length(gene_overlap)/(length(cr_like_em_genes))
[1] 1

When you look at shared cells only, cr-like and cr-like-em identify the exact same genes. However, we had seen an increase in the genes detected/cell. It looks like the actual number of genes doesn’t increase, but the coverage of some genes across each the cells increases, leading to a slight increase in the number of genes/cell with cr-like-em.

Here we can see that across the board, the cr-like-em resolution results in what appears to be an increase in the percentage of cells genes are detected in when compared to cr-like. Does this still hold if we remove genes that are only detected in 5% of cells?

If we only look at genes detected in > 5% of cells we no longer see a clear difference between the two resolutions.
